{
  "What is bioaccumulation?": "",
  "The process of organisms reproducing rapidly in polluted environments": "",
  "The buildup of a substance in an organism's body over time because it is absorbed faster than it is eliminated": "",
  "The natural breakdown of toxins by bacteria": "",
  "The spread of pollutants through the atmosphere": "",
  "Bioaccumulation occurs when an organism absorbs a substance (such as a toxin or heavy metal) at a rate faster than it can metabolize or excrete it, causing the substance to build up in tissues over the organism's lifetime.": "",
  "How does biomagnification differ from bioaccumulation?": "",
  "Biomagnification is the increase in concentration of a substance at each successive trophic level in a food chain": "",
  "Biomagnification decreases toxin levels at higher trophic levels": "",
  "Biomagnification only affects plants": "",
  "There is no difference between the two terms": "",
  "While bioaccumulation refers to buildup within a single organism, biomagnification describes the increasing concentration of a persistent substance at each higher trophic level in a food chain as predators consume contaminated prey.": "",
  "Which banned pesticide is one of the most well-known examples of biomagnification?": "",
  "Malathion": "",
  "Atrazine": "",
  "DDT": "",
  "Glyphosate": "",
  "DDT is the classic example of biomagnification. It accumulated through aquatic food chains, reaching concentrations millions of times higher in top predators like bald eagles, causing eggshell thinning and population declines.": "",
  "Which heavy metal biomagnifies through aquatic food chains and poses a significant health risk to humans who eat contaminated fish?": "",
  "Mercury (as methylmercury)": "",
  "Copper when": "",
  "Iron, based": "",
  "Zinc, based": "",
  "Mercury, particularly in its organic form methylmercury, biomagnifies through aquatic food chains. Top predatory fish like tuna and swordfish can contain mercury concentrations over a million times higher than surrounding water.": "",
  "Why are top predators most at risk from biomagnification?": "",
  "They have weaker immune systems than other organisms": "",
  "They consume many contaminated prey organisms, accumulating the highest concentrations of persistent toxins": "",
  "They are directly exposed to more pollution in their habitat": "",
  "They cannot metabolize any toxins at all": "",
  "Top predators eat large quantities of prey that have already bioaccumulated toxins. Because the toxins are persistent (not broken down), each meal adds more, and the predator's position at the top means it accumulates the combined toxin load of many organisms.": "",
  "What property must a chemical have to biomagnify through food chains?": "",
  "It must be a gas at room temperature": "",
  "It must be water-soluble and easily excreted": "",
  "It must be radioactive": "",
  "It must be persistent (resistant to breakdown) and fat-soluble (lipophilic)": "",
  "Chemicals that biomagnify are persistent (they resist metabolic breakdown and environmental degradation) and lipophilic (fat-soluble), so they accumulate in fatty tissues rather than being dissolved in water and excreted.": "",
  "How did DDT biomagnification affect bald eagle populations?": "",
  "DDT caused eggshell thinning, leading to egg breakage during incubation and reproductive failure": "",
  "DDT directly poisoned adult eagles": "",
  "DDT caused eagles to lose their ability to fly": "",
  "DDT destroyed the eagles' food sources": "",
  "High concentrations of DDT's breakdown product DDE interfered with calcium deposition in eagle eggshells, making them so thin they broke during incubation. This reproductive failure caused dramatic population declines until DDT was banned in 1972.": "",
  "What are persistent organic pollutants (POPs)?": "",
  "Biodegradable plastics used in packaging": "",
  "Organic fertilizers that break down quickly in soil": "",
  "Natural plant chemicals that repel insects": "",
  "Toxic chemical compounds that resist environmental degradation, bioaccumulate, and pose long-term health risks": "",
  "Persistent organic pollutants (POPs) are toxic chemicals that resist degradation, bioaccumulate in fatty tissues, and can travel long distances through the atmosphere. Examples include DDT, PCBs, dioxins, and certain flame retardants.": "",
  "What international agreement addresses the elimination of persistent organic pollutants?": "",
  "Montreal Protocol": "",
  "Kyoto Protocol": "",
  "Paris Agreement": "",
  "Stockholm Convention": "",
  "The Stockholm Convention on Persistent Organic Pollutants, adopted in 2001, is a global treaty to protect human health and the environment from POPs by eliminating or restricting their production, use, and release.": "",
